---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import HeroSection from "../components/HeroSection.astro";
import TextSection from "../components/TextSection.astro";
import CTASection from "../components/CTASection.astro";
import { endorsementsURL, volunteerURL } from "../utils/urls";
---

<Layout title="About">
	<HeroSection
		title="Meet Alysse"
		subtitle="A lifelong educator fighting for the students the system wasn't designed for"
		centered={true}
	/>

	<TextSection backgroundColor="white" maxWidth="medium" content="">
		<p class="mb-4 text-lg">
			Alysse Castro is the Alameda County Superintendent of Schools, a lifelong
			educator who has built her career fighting for the students the system
			wasn't designed for. A former classroom teacher, principal, and county
			leader, Alysse has dedicated over two decades to transforming the
			conditions that hold vulnerable students back ‚Äî and building the systems
			that allow them to thrive. She brings a rare blend of deep instructional
			expertise, technical mastery of Ed Code and school finance, and an
			unwavering commitment to equity.
		</p>
		<p class="text-lg">
			Since taking office as County Superintendent, Alysse has led with a simple
			belief: students who face the greatest barriers deserve the strongest,
			most innovative public systems. Her leadership has been defined by turning
			red tape into real solutions, modernizing outdated structures, and
			delivering measurable results for young people who are too often
			overlooked ‚Äî youth in juvenile court schools, students experiencing
			homelessness, multilingual learners, and those navigating generational
			poverty.
		</p>
	</TextSection>

	<TextSection
		heading="Delivering System-Changing Results for the Students Who Need It Most"
		backgroundColor="white"
		maxWidth="medium"
		content=""
	>
		<p class="mb-6">
			Under Alysse's leadership, the Alameda County Office of Education
			sponsored and passed its first-ever piece of legislation ‚Äî and it passed
			unanimously. <strong>AB 2181</strong>, now awaiting signature, ensures
			students in juvenile court schools have a full pathway to a high school
			diploma, correcting decades-old gaps in the Education Code. The bill
			expands graduation opportunities, reduces unnecessary barriers, and
			provides new avenues for students whose educational journeys were
			interrupted by the juvenile justice system. The work behind AB 2181
			reflects exactly who Alysse is: an advocate who knows how to navigate the
			complexity of state law ‚Äî and who uses that expertise to dismantle
			systemic inequities.
		</p>

		<div class="p-6 bg-blue-50 rounded-lg border-l-4 border-blue-600">
			<h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-blue-900 mb-3">
				üèÜ California Golden Bell Award
			</h3>
			<p class="mb-4">
				Alysse also led Alameda County to win a California Golden Bell Award for
				its groundbreaking workforce diversification effort, the <strong
					>Professional Advancement and Training Hub (PATH)</strong
				>.
			</p>
			<p class="mb-3">Launched just two years ago, PATH has already:</p>
			<ul class="space-y-2 ml-4">
				<li>
					‚úì Helped <strong>1,500 residents</strong> plan careers in education
				</li>
				<li>
					‚úì Funded credentials for <strong
						>130 multilingual intern teachers</strong>
				</li>
				<li>‚úì Supported <strong>100 new instructional aides</strong></li>
				<li>
					‚úì Graduated <strong>54 residents</strong> from a local teacher residency
				</li>
				<li>‚úì Helped <strong>200 educators</strong> earn clear credentials</li>
			</ul>
			<p class="mt-4 italic">
				The program is now considered a statewide model for how government can
				build an educator workforce that reflects and serves diverse communities
				‚Äî and solve staffing shortages with local talent.
			</p>
		</div>
	</TextSection>

	<TextSection
		heading="Transforming Systems by Centering the Most Vulnerable"
		backgroundColor="white"
		maxWidth="medium"
		content=""
	>
		<p class="mb-6">
			Alysse's tenure has also brought a fundamental reframing of what it means
			to be a county office of education. She has reoriented ACOE's mission
			around the students who have historically been last in line for resources
			‚Äî and the educators who serve them. Through a countywide vision and set of
			strategic priorities, she has:
		</p>

		<div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
			<div class="p-4">
				<h4 class="font-bold text-blue-900 mb-2">
					üìä Centered Priority Populations
				</h4>
				<p class="text-sm text-gray-700">
					Ensuring data, funding, and professional supports are aligned to the
					students with the highest needs
				</p>
			</div>
			<div class="p-4">
				<h4 class="font-bold text-blue-900 mb-2">
					üîß Redesigned Interventions
				</h4>
				<p class="text-sm text-gray-700">
					Providing differentiated, technically strong, and instructionally
					grounded support for struggling districts and schools
				</p>
			</div>
			<div class="p-4">
				<h4 class="font-bold text-blue-900 mb-2">üí∞ Maximized Resources</h4>
				<p class="text-sm text-gray-700">
					Unlocking new funding streams and ensuring districts get timely,
					accurate, student-centered support
				</p>
			</div>
			<div class="p-4">
				<h4 class="font-bold text-blue-900 mb-2">üí° Culture of Innovation</h4>
				<p class="text-sm text-gray-700">
					Empowering staff, districts, and community partners to pilot solutions
					rooted in equity and accountability
				</p>
			</div>
		</div>

		<p class="mt-6 text-lg italic text-center">
			Her "students-first, systems-always" approach is known countywide: she is
			warm and collaborative, but also direct, technically adept, and unafraid
			to challenge practices that fail students.
		</p>
	</TextSection>

	<TextSection
		heading="A Leader Rooted in Community and Committed to Justice"
		backgroundColor="white"
		maxWidth="medium"
		content=""
	>
		<p class="mb-4">
			Alysse's work is shaped by her early years as an educator in schools
			serving students experiencing homelessness, foster youth, emerging
			bilinguals, and students navigating trauma and instability. These
			experiences built her belief that public education is the most powerful
			tool we have to disrupt the predetermination of failure for children
			growing up in communities impacted by violence and poverty ‚Äî and that
			leaders must be bold enough to change systems that aren't working.
		</p>
		<p class="mb-4">
			Alysse is a self-professed "school finance nerd" who can translate complex
			fiscal structures into real opportunities for kids, and a trusted
			statewide expert on Ed Code who uses regulatory expertise not as a
			barrier, but as a lever for equity. She is honored to be invited by
			elected officials and labor leaders alike to help build understanding and
			trust in complex school budgets.
		</p>
		<p class="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-900">
			Alysse continues to lead with clarity, courage, and heart ‚Äî championing
			the students who have the least, demanding more of the systems that serve
			them, and delivering results that prove what is possible when we put the
			most vulnerable children at the center of every decision.
		</p>
	</TextSection>

	<CTASection
		heading="Support Alysse's Vision"
		description="Join us in building a more equitable education system for all Alameda County students"
		primaryButtonText="Get Involved"
		primaryButtonLink={volunteerURL}
		secondaryButtonText="View Endorsements"
		secondaryButtonLink={endorsementsURL}
		backgroundColor="gradient"
	/>
</Layout>
